Companies, of which himself commanded the first, and the Duke of
_Courland_ the second. I was of this second Company, and we went
sometimes to perform our Military Exercises at _Lutzelbourg_ before the
Queen, who lovaEuro(TM)d to see the Prince her Son display the first Fruits of his
Military Genius. We also acted some Comedies before her; for the Princess
aimaEuro(TM)d to inspire the Prince her Son with a delicate Taste, even in
Pleasures.

aEuro(TM)Twas at this time that a Storm arose at Court against the Count _de
Wartemberg_ Great Chamberlain, and lately declaraEuro(TM)d Prime Minister, which
threatenaEuro(TM)d his Ruin; but it spent itself upon those only who had raisaEuro(TM)d
it. The principal Authors of the Cabal were the Count _de Lottum_, M.
----, and the Grand Marshal, who had been for a long time the Great
ChamberlainaEuro(TM)s sworn Enemy. The Count _de Wesen_, my Father-in-law, was
pitchaEuro(TM)d upon by these Gentlemen to raise the first Prejudices in the
KingaEuro(TM)s Mind against this Minister. I have had the Honor to acquaint you,
_Madame_, that the Countess _de Wartemberg_ always wishaEuro(TM)d well to M. _de
Wesen_ of which the advantagious Match she had procuraEuro(TM)d for him was a very
convincing Proof. One would have thought therefore after such great
Service, that he ought in Gratitude to have devoted himself entirely to
the Fortune of the Count her Husband. But my Father-in-law puffaEuro(TM)d up by
the Choice which the CountaEuro(TM)s Enemies had made of him, forgot his Duty and
his Interest, and accepted a Commission for the undertaking of which he
had in truth all the necessary Temerity, but not that Judgment nor that
Favor, which was absolutely requisite for conducting so ticklish an
Affair.

The King had a real Love for M. _de Wartemberg_, yet he sometimes made him
feel his ill Humors. The Prince seemaEuro(TM)d one day to be so angry with him,
and spoke of him to my Father-in-law with so much Resentment, that the
latter thought he had now a fair Opportunity to ruin the Count. He said to
the King, that the whole Court was surprizaEuro(TM)d at his extraordinary Kindness
to a Minister who every day abusaEuro(TM)d his Name in the Oppression of the
People, and in the Commission of a thousand Acts of Injustice against his
faithful Servants; that his Rapines were excessive; and that his WifeaEuro(TM)s
Extravagance was so great, that he could shew by the Accounts of the
Comptrollers of the Kitchen, that the Great ChamberlainaEuro(TM)s Table cost more
than his MajestyaEuro(TM)s. _I know very well_, added M. _de Wesen, that if the
Prime Minister should hear of what I have now had the Honor to say to your
Majesty, I am undone; but if I held my peace, I thought I should be
wanting in my Duty; and what I have asserted I am ready to prove._

The King heard what he said very attentively, and my Father-in-law was so
vain as to think he had made Impression enough upon him to strike M. _de
Wartemberg_ quite out of his Favor; but this shallow Statesman, my
Father-in-law, did not consider that a Prince who complains of his
Favorite is not always disposaEuro(TM)d to receive the ill Impressions that others
are ready to give of him. Whether the King therefore thought after this
manner, or whether he was shockaEuro(TM)d at the Ingratitude of M. _de Wesen_, who
owaEuro(TM)d his Fortune to M. _de Wartemberg_, he told the Minister the
Conversation that had passaEuro(TM)d, but assuraEuro(TM)d him that he did not give Credit
to the Report; and that if he pleasaEuro(TM)d he would take a Revenge on the Man
that had made it.

The crafty Minister affected at that time an Air of Moderation, which cost
him the less Pains because he was an excellent Comedian. He said to the
King that he thought himself sufficiently revengaEuro(TM)d, by the little Heed his
Majesty gave to the scandalous Tales which his Enemies gave out against
him, and he desiraEuro(TM)d his Majesty to pardon those who had offeraEuro(TM)d to abuse
his Goodness, for the sake of oppressing him. Thus did he for a while
conceal the keenest Resentment under the Mask of the most forgiving
Temper; being resolvaEuro(TM)d in his Heart to ruin those who had employaEuro(TM)d M. _de
Wesen_, thoaEuro(TM) they were protected by the Queen, but especially to make
their Tool feel all the Weight of his Vengeance.

A Journey which the King took to _Goltz_, one of his Hunting-Seats, near
the Fortress of _Custrin_, gave him a good Opportunity for it. Being alone
with the King in the same Coach, he put him so much out of conceit with M.
_de Wesen_, that when he arrivaEuro(TM)d at _Goltz_, all that came to wait on him,
as he alighted out of the Coach, perceivaEuro(TM)d he was in an ill Humor.
Contrary to his usual custom, he spoke to no body, only he orderaEuro(TM)d my
Father-in-law to give his Attendance. When he had sat down, he scarce
touchaEuro(TM)d the Bread, but he found fault with it, and complained of it to M.
_de Wesen_, as the Person who had the Direction of what came to his Table.
M. _de Wesen_ said to the King, That aEuro(TM)twas true the Bread was not as it
usaEuro(TM)d to be, because the Carriage of the Pantry broke down by the way, and
the Baker came too late to Town to provide more. The King not well pleasaEuro(TM)d
with this Answer, said, he was weary of being ill servaEuro(TM)d, and that he
expected every one shouaEuro(TM)d do their Duty. At the same time he threw his
Napkin on the Ground. M. _de Wesen_ fetchaEuro(TM)d another, and offeraEuro(TM)d it to the
King, but he would not take it, and orderaEuro(TM)d him to be gone that Moment out
of his Presence. Two Hours after, M. _de Wesen_ was arrested by an Exempt
of the Life-Guards, who conducted him in his Coach under a Guard to
_Custrin_, the Capital of the New Marquisate, situate upon the _Oder_.
There my Father-in-law was kept as a State-Criminal, and the Minister sent
Orders to the Aulic Counsellor to go to my MotheraEuro(TM)s House, and clap a Seal
upon her HusbandaEuro(TM)s Effects. She was at that time in the Country, and my
Brother happenaEuro(TM)d to be at Church with our Governor, so that I was alone in
the House when those Gentlemen came to execute their Order. After they had
shewaEuro(TM)d it to me, they askaEuro(TM)d me which was my Father-in-lawaEuro(TM)s Apartment,
that they might not be obligaEuro(TM)d to put the Seal upon every thing. I made no
scruple to shew it to them, and as they withdrew they left me a Writing
which was an Order to my Mother not to come to Court, nor to sollicite her
HusbandaEuro(TM)s Liberty. I sent immediately For my Governor, that he might go
with this disagreeable News to my Mother, whose Surprize was as great as
her Sorrow; for as she had an entire Love for her Husband, so she knew
nothing of his Intrigues against the Minister, to whom she thought he was
all along devoted. As the KingaEuro(TM)s Order tied up her Hands, and hinderaEuro(TM)d her
from coming to Court, I was chargaEuro(TM)d to do what I could there, to obtain my
Father-in-lawaEuro(TM)s Liberty.

One day as the Queen made an Entertainment at _Lutzelbourg_ for the King,
I presented a Petition to him, in my MotheraEuro(TM)s Name, intreating him to
remove the Seal from her Effects, and the Guard from her House; and that
his Majesty would be pleasaEuro(TM)d to appoint Commissioners to try her Husband;
to the end, that if guilty, he might be punishaEuro(TM)d, or if innocent, that he
might be set at liberty. My Youth, and the Tears which I shed at the
Delivery of this Petition, melted the KingaEuro(TM)s Heart, who told me, That he
would do what my Mother desiraEuro(TM)d, for her sake only; that he sympathizaEuro(TM)d in
her Affliction; but that her Husband had so justly provokaEuro(TM)d him, that he
could not avoid making him sensible of his Indignation: That withal, he
