was perfectly reconcilaEuro(TM)d to him; but I was not at all pleasaEuro(TM)d with Madam
_de R----_. I saw plainly that I was betrayaEuro(TM)d. I had fresh Cause to
suspect her every day, and yet I hugged the Chains wherewith she had bound
me; in which I sufficiently confuted the vulgar Error of those who assert,
that People never love heartily but once. I ought, however, to reflect a
little upon this last Amour, which was extremely hurtful to me. Madam _de
R----_ was so extravagant that a Man could not be upon good Terms with
her, without being, at an excessive Expence. To support my self I borrowaEuro(TM)d
Money every where, till eaEuro(TM)er long I knew not where to find Lenders. On the
other hand my Creditors began to make me frequent Visits, till they were
tiraEuro(TM)d with my continually putting them off from one time to another, and
then truly they resolvaEuro(TM)d to proceed against me by Law; and at length took
