her Royal Highness that he had been misrepresented to her. _What!_ said
Madame, _will you offer to deny that he had his Hand cut off for
counterfeiting the Sign-Manual of the King of +Denmark+?_ As I knew the
Adventure of _S----_ at the _Danish_ Court, and that his was not a Crime
of such a nature; and as, moreover, I knew that the Loss of his Right Arm
was owing to a Fall that he had receivaEuro(TM)d, I represented to _Madame_, that
I should have thought the cutting off of his Hand Punishment enough in all
reason for the Crime of which she suspected _S----_; but that
nevertheless, his Arm was cut off near the Shoulder. _Alas_! said the
Princess, _thataEuro(TM)s because it was cut a second time. But, Madame_, I
instantly replyaEuro(TM)d, _How could your Royal Highness favor a Man that was
capable of such a Fraud? I have my Reasons for it_, said she. I did not
venture to indulge my Curiosity further. But in fine, this M. _de S----_
who was to the last degree abhorraEuro(TM)d, obtainaEuro(TM)d what he desiraEuro(TM)d; whereas,
for my part, as well as I was wishaEuro(TM)d, I could not possibly obtain so much
as a positive Denial, which would at least have servaEuro(TM)d to undeceive me,
and to make me look out for Preferment from another Quarter.

While _Madame_ was at _St. Cloud_, the Duchess of _Berry_ resided at
_Meudon_, thoaEuro(TM) sometimes she came to _Paris_. I had the Honor of paying my
Compliments to this Princess very often. She was good-naturaEuro(TM)d and
generous, and very free to ask Favors of the Regent her Father, who seldom
denyaEuro(TM)d her; so that whoever had her Protection, was in a sure way to be
advancaEuro(TM)d. The Count _de R----_, a young Man of Quality, and who was just
enteraEuro(TM)d as a Lieutenant in that PrincessaEuro(TM)s Guards, knew better than any
body how to gain his MistressaEuro(TM)s Favor. I knew him some time before this
