Precaution. The Czar thought this House also too richly furnishaEuro(TM)d, and
notwithstanding all they could say he would not lie in a magnificent Bed
which was put up in the Apartment that was to be his, but causaEuro(TM)d a little
Bed to be set up for himself in the Wardrobe. Next day the Regent came and
paid him a Visit, when the Prince _de Kourakin_ the CzaraEuro(TM)s Ambassador to
_Holland_ servaEuro(TM)d for their Interpreter. The Visit lasted near an Hour, and
there all the Ceremonial was settled that was to be observaEuro(TM)d to the
_Russian_ Monarch.

After this the King went to see him first, being accompanied from the
Palace of the _Thuilleries_, with the chief Lords and Officers of the
Crown. The Czar receivaEuro(TM)d his Majesty as he alighted from the Coach, and
took him in his Arms with a Transport of Fondness; at which the young
Monarch seemaEuro(TM)d a little surprizaEuro(TM)d. He said to the Czar, _That he was very
glad to see him safe arrived at +Paris+; that he wishaEuro(TM)d him Pleasure as
long as he staid in his Dominions; that he should have the same Respect
paid to him as to himself, and that he had given Orders for the
Court-Service always to give way to his_. Then the two Monarchs went hand
in hand into a Chamber where two Chairs of State were placaEuro(TM)d. The Czar
being the Stranger sate on the Right Hand. The Duke _du Maine_ and the
Marshal _de Villeroy_ stood behind the KingaEuro(TM)s Chair of State, and answeraEuro(TM)d
the Questions which the Czar askaEuro(TM)d his Majesty. After a short Visit the
King rose first, and was accompanied to his Coach by the Czar, who at
taking Leave of his Majesty caught him up again in his Arms, and hoisting
him higher than his Head, said, _He wishaEuro(TM)d that his Grandeur and Power
might surpass that of the late King_ Lewis XIV. He helpaEuro(TM)d the King into
his Coach, and did not return till it movaEuro(TM)d off.

Next day the Czar went to the _Thuilleries_ with the same Train as the
King has when he goes abroad, and rode in the KingaEuro(TM)s Coach attended by the
chief Lords of his Court, who sat over-against him, and at the
Coach-Doors. As soon as he enteraEuro(TM)d the Court, the King went to the Gate of
the Castle, receivaEuro(TM)d him at his landing, and then conducted him to his
Apartment, always giving the Czar the Right Hand. I never saw more People
at the _Thuilleries_ than there were on that day, insomuch that the two
Monarchs had scarce room to pass. The Czar shewaEuro(TM)d a prodigious Care of the
King, kept him up by one Hand, and wavaEuro(TM)d the other to keep off such as
were apt to croud too near him. After a Visit no longer than that which
the King made to the Prince, his Majesty reconducted him to the Coach,
and the Czar returnaEuro(TM)d to his House with the same Train that had
accompanied him. When that Prince returnaEuro(TM)d to his Apartment, he told the
Marshal, _That he was very much surprizaEuro(TM)d at the infinite Croud of People
in the way_. To which the Marshal made Answer, _That the +French+ had so
great a Veneration for his Person, and so high an Idea of his illustrious
Qualities, that no wonder they were so eager to see a Prince, who they
knew beforehand was deserving of their Admiration_. The Czar seemaEuro(TM)d very
well pleasaEuro(TM)d with this Answer, yet he desiraEuro(TM)d, _That for the future, when
he went abroad, the People might be obligaEuro(TM)d to keep out of his way_. He
paid a Visit next day to the Regent and to _Madame_. The latter talkaEuro(TM)d to
him for two Hours in _High-Dutch_, and the Czar answeraEuro(TM)d the Princess in
_Low-Dutch_. When he was withdrawn he said to M. _de S----_, _That
+Madame+ was extremely inquisitive; that she wanted to knew every thing;
and that she had askaEuro(TM)d him too many Questions; but that after all, he told
her no more than what he was willing she should know_.

The Czar was very curious to see every thing that was worth seeing in and
about _Paris_. He informaEuro(TM)d himself of every thing, and took care to write
every thing in his Pocket-book that he thought remarkable. He rose at
Day-break, and rambled about from one Place to another till Night. To
prevent all manner of Incumbrance he chose to make use of none but the
Marshal _de Tesse_aEuro(TM)s Coaches, thoaEuro(TM) that Nobleman would have been well
enough contented without such Preference, because he killaEuro(TM)d several of his
Horses; and the poor Marshal himself must have sunk under the Fatigue of
the perpetual Motion that he was obligaEuro(TM)d to, if the Czar had staid much
longer; but this Monarch lost no time, and examinaEuro(TM)d every thing with equal
Nicety and Dispatch, because he intended to be gone as soon as he had
satisfyaEuro(TM)d his Curiosity.

The Court sparaEuro(TM)d nothing to pay this Prince all due Honors. The Regent for
this purpose orderaEuro(TM)d a general Review of all the KingaEuro(TM)s Houshold Troops,
and of the _French_ and _Swiss_ Guards in the Walks of _Roule_ and in the
_Elysian Fields_. The Czar repairaEuro(TM)d thither on horseback, and aEuro(TM)twas
expected he would have staid out the whole Review; but he only rode
briskly in the Front of the first Line, without casting his Eyes on the
Troops, and then clapping Spurs to his Horse, without paying any
Compliment to the Regent, he returnaEuro(TM)d full Gallop to _Paris_. From thence
he went directly to _St. Ouen_, where the Duke _de Tresmes_, First
Gentleman of the Bed-Chamber, and Governor of _Paris_, gave him an
Entertainment, with which he seemaEuro(TM)d better pleasaEuro(TM)d than with the Review.
He was loth to consent to the Admission of the Ladies into the Orangery
where the Table was spread, and only spoke to Madame _de Bethune_,
Daughter of the Duke _de Tresmes_, for which Distinction she was obligaEuro(TM)d
to M. _de Bethune_, who having been a good while in _Poland_, talkaEuro(TM)d the
_Polish_ Language very well, which procuraEuro(TM)d him the Honor of being able to
converse with his Czarish Majesty. The chief Noblemen, after the Example
of the Duke _de Tresmes_, made Entertainments for the _Russian_ Monarch.
The Duke Regent also preparaEuro(TM)d a Grand Feast for him at _St. Cloud_; but
just as the Czar was setting out from _Paris_, he was seizaEuro(TM)d with a
violent Fit of the Cholic, which hinderaEuro(TM)d his going abroad; nor do I know
